  <p><ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate this indefinite integral using linearity, the power
        rule, and/or the tables of anti-derivatives.  (3) 
      </p>
      <me>
        \int \frac{1}{1+x^2} dx 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate this indefinite integral using linearity, the power
        rule, and/or the tables of anti-derivatives.  (3) 
      </p>
      <me>
        \int (3x)^2 dx 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate this indefinite integral using linearity, the power
        rule, and/or the tables of anti-derivatives.  (3) 
      </p>
      <me>
        \int \sin x + \cos x dx 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate this indefinite integral using linearity, the power
        rule, and/or the tables of anti-derivatives.  (3) 
      </p>
      <me>
        \int \sqrt[5]{x} dx 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate this definite integrals using linearity, the power
        rules, and/or the tables of anti-derivatives. (4)
      </p>
      <me>
        \int_{-1}^6 \frac{x^2}{4} + \frac{x}{2} dx 
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate this definite integrals using linearity, the power
        rules, and/or the tables of anti-derivatives. (4)
      </p>
      <me>
        \int_{-\pi}^{\pi} \sin x + 1 dx
      </me>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Calculate this definite integrals using linearity, the power
        rules, and/or the tables of anti-derivatives. (4)
      </p>
      <me>
